
Marco Tulio Medina a Honduran physician, neurologist, educator and researcher born in Tegucigalpa, Honduras on September 19th,1959. He is the Director of the Neurology Training Program, at the National Autonomous University of Honduras (a World Federation of Neurology educational Pilot Program).He made his training in Neurology at the National Institute of Neurology in Mexico; Pediatric epileptology at the Saint Paul Center, Marseille, France under the guidance of Dr Charlotte Dravet; Adult Epileptology at the University of Los Angeles, California (UCLA) with Prof. Antonio Delgado-Escueta and Clinical Neurophysiology at the Aix-Marseille University. 

Prof. Medina is the Chairman of the World Federation of Neurology Education Subcommittee on Spanish Speaking Countries, President of the Salvador Moncada Foundation for the Advancement of Science, Founder and Past President of the Honduran Epilepsy Society and Honduran Neurological Association, Past President of the Ibero American Stroke Society and Chairman of the ILAE Commission on  Latin American Affairs. 

He published more than 100 papers in national and international journals, more than 25 chapters and edited several books and supplement journals including: Myoclonic Epilepsies in the Advances in Neurology series (2005), Actualidades en Las Epìlepsias in Mexico (2002), Epilepsias in Centro America (2001). Neurocysticercosis ( Neurosurgical Focus, 2002), etc He is member of the Editorial Board of the Revista de Neurologia (Spain), International Stroke Journal, Acta Neurológica Colombiana (Associated Editor), Revista Ecuatoriana de Neurología, Archivo de Neurociencias (Mexico), Revista Chilena de Neuropsiquiatría, Electronic Journal of Biomedicine and Reviewer of the European Journal of Neurology, Epilepsia, Cerebrovascular Disease and Neuroepidemiology . He co discovered the EFHC1 gene and received the National Prize of Science “Jose Cecilio del Valle” in 1996 by the Honduran Government, the Latin American Trelles Award on Epidemiology Research (2003) , the Award in Clinical Research at the National Institute of Neurology in Mexico( 2006) among others. 

 




